collections.name: Cancan Girls
collections.description:
McGilliam  
Belgium, 1954
With an impressive start in the art world, McGilliam won the international school prize for painting at the young age of sixteen. His artistic journey has led him through many creative periods, from intense fervor to moments of stagnation and introspection. But as he himself says: “The eye always sees something that evokes feelings.”
McGilliam's original style, rooted in pop art and infused with expressive elements, is not limited by paint or one-dimensional materials. His works are exceptional: they radiate an extraordinarily clean and pure aesthetic, with an expression that reaches into higher dimensions.
In the language of art, McGilliam knows how to communicate with his creative talents, leaving an undeniable impression in the world of visual arts. His visual masterpieces invite exploration of the depths of human experience.
G. Luyten (curator)

collections.name: Toddler's Canvas
collections.description:
"Every wall is a canvas, and every child is an artist in the making."

"Toddler’s Canvas" is a heartwarming NFT collection that captures the raw, unfiltered creativity of a 2-year-old. These pieces, drawn spontaneously on a wall, reflect the purest form of artistic expression—free from rules, expectations, and constraints. Instead of covering up this fleeting moment, it is being preserved forever as digital art, celebrating the beauty of unstructured imagination.

Each NFT in this collection is more than just a drawing—it’s a memory, a story, and a tribute to the magic of childhood. A reminder that true creativity is boundless, and sometimes, the best masterpieces come from the smallest hands.

collections.name: Prigione Ottica
collections.description:
"Prigione Ottica" is a minimalist and conceptual digital composition that blurs the line between the organic and the mechanical, the real and the imagined. At its core, the piece presents a surreal structure — a form that resembles both a spacecraft and the sinuous body of a marine creature. Emerging from this hybrid entity is a haunting face with two piercing red eyes, fixed in a gaze that is both accusatory and imploring.
This is not a portrait, but a mirror.
The red eyes are symbols of surveillance, of awareness, of silent suffering — trapped in a reality where the individual is both prisoner and jailer. The sleek, ambiguous form that surrounds them evokes a world that is futuristic yet decaying, cold yet suffocating. It is a prison not made of walls, but of perception.
